   <mods:abstract>The death of his grandchild and poor health have delayed his answer. If
            able, he will experiment with plaster; the results from its use in the garden this
            spring have been good. Speculates on the reason for its success. National interest in
            agriculture has improved greatly since the Revolution. Agrees that the Spaniards deserve
            credit for their spirit; quotes the late Abbe Mably who said of them: "ils sont plus
            Hommes que nous." Wishes them success but does not think it probable. Perilous times
            have fallen on Europe and Napoleon is the Nebuchadnezzar of the day. Dark clouds from
            that tempest have lately obscured the American political sky, but he does not apprehend
            anything like "overturn."</mods:abstract>
